Other news includes a US writers' strike, a soldier shooting a politician in Africa, Serena Williams announcing her pregnancy at the Met Gala, and the discovery of seven dead bodies in Oklahoma. The most read stories include the potential intelligence of AI chatbots surpassing humans and the eye-catching looks at the Met Gala.

Content summary part#1: The text includes various foreign news stories, including the death of a Palestinian hunger striker in an Israeli prison, rockets being fired at Israel by Islamic Jihad, a soldier shooting a politician he was guarding, and the discovery of seven dead bodies in rural Oklahoma. It also mentions that artificial intelligence chatbots may soon be more intelligent than humans, and that Russia has suffered 20,000 troop deaths and 80,000 wounded soldiers in fighting since December. Additionally, the text includes news about Japan banning upskirting in stronger sex crime laws, and the warning from the US Treasury Secretary that the country could run out of cash in a month if it hits the debt ceiling.

Raw content part#2: Latest UpdatesPosted at 7:017:01'Khartoum water, markets and banking apps are back'Eyewitness in the west of Sudan's capitalNewsdayBBC World ServiceTagreed Abdin thinks about leaving Sudan every day, but for now in her corner of the capital, people are trying to "return to normalcy" in small ways.Her local vegetable market re-opened two days ago in western Khartoum. She says she has running water in her home and plenty of rice and pasta left over from Ramadan.The neighbourhood is "relatively quiet", Ms Abdin tells the BBC, between periods of very heavy shelling, military planes flying overhead and anti-aircraft missiles being fired.Sudanese people have mostly been relying on cash since the debit card system went down, she explains, but the main banking app is now working again:Quote Message: I just got a message that the mobile bank apps have started running again, so I tried it out and I made a transaction to make sure. However people also use it to buy phone credit and make payments [for pre-paid electricity] - so I'm not sure if they were able to fix that part." from Tagreed Abdin Resident of KhartoumI just got a message that the mobile bank apps have started running again, so I tried it out and I made a transaction to make sure. However people also use it to buy phone credit and make payments [for pre-paid electricity] - so I'm not sure if they were able to fix that part."Tagreed AbdinResident of KhartoumFor now, she tells the BBC she is staying put and starting "preliminary planning what to do in case of an emergency".ReutersCopyright: ReutersThis was the scene in northern Khartoum on MondayImage caption: This was the scene in northern Khartoum on MondayMore on Sudan's crisis:'Fighter jets are roaring over my home in Omdurman'Article share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 6:356:35Singer-songwriter Gordon Lightfoot dies aged 84The Canadian musician's songs were covered by artists including Elvis Presley and Barbara Streisand.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 6:336:33Kenyan doomsday cult leader freed and rearrestedDorcas WangiraBBC News, NairobiAFPCopyright: AFPPaul Mackenzie, in pink, made an appearance at the hearing in MalindiImage caption: Paul Mackenzie, in pink, made an appearance at the hearing in MalindiThe
leader of a Kenyan cult group and six others have been rearrested minutes after
a court in Malindi released them.Magistrate Ivy Wasike freed Paul Nthenge Mackenzie and his suspected accomplices after an application by the prosecution
to close the file.State
prosecutor Vivian Kambaga said she wanted them to be tried in another court - on charges that will include terrorism. They have been driven to neighbouring Mombasa county, which is further south along the coast.They were initially charged with murder, radicalisation and threatening public safety after more
than 100 followers of the cult group were found in mass graves last month.Mr Mackenzie, the leader of the group, was accused of encouraging
them to starve themselves to death. He denies any wrongdoing.A post-mortem report showed that the some of
the victims were also killed through suffocation and strangulation.Article share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 6:016:01Seven bodies found in US search for missing teensBy Brandon DrenonBBC NewsPolice searching for two missing teenagers in rural Oklahoma say they have found seven dead bodies.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 5:535:53Palestinian hunger striker dies in Israel prisonBy David GrittenBBC NewsRockets are fired at Israel after Islamic Jihad threatens revenge over the death of a senior figure.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 5:405:40Japan to ban upskirting in stronger sex crime lawsBy Kelly NgBBC NewsThe bill outlaws secretly filming someone for sexual exploitation and is set to be passed in June.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 5:075:07Allow regional bloc to resolve Sudan row - Eritrean leaderTeklemariam BekitBBC News TigrinyaReutersCopyright: ReutersEritrea says the crisis in Sudan can be resolved by the neighbouring countriesImage caption: Eritrea says the crisis in Sudan can be resolved by the neighbouring countriesEritrean President Isaias Afwerki says the East African regional grouping, the Intergovernmental Authority on Development (Igad), should be given priority in resolving the ongoing crisis in Sudan.He says that while that the current situation in Sudan is a matter of global concern and
individual countries may express their
interest, the Igad's initiative can assist the Sudanese people to transition to a new political disposition that aligns with their aspirations.The president said there was an urgent need for the "tragic
and deplorable conflict" in Sudan to come to an immediate end and for there to be an unitary defence and security organ in the country.He says Eritrea is willing to provide
its best assistance to address the crisis in Sudan, but the people
should also be allowed to address their challenges independently.Mr Isaias said Eritrean sea, land borders as well as its airspace were open for Sudanese and others affected by the current conflict. He, however, insisted that
Eritrea was not willing
to establish "refugee shops" but was willing to provide modest assistance to the Sudanese people.He said the ongoing conflict was the result of the military
leaders engaged in a power struggle without fulfilling their responsibility
to ensure a peaceful transition to an elected government.Article share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 4:544:54Australia to ban recreational vapingBy Tiffanie TurnbullBBC News, SydneyThe government says vaping has become a huge epidemic, particularly affecting young people.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 4:374:37Met Gala 2023: Stars celebrate Karl LagerfeldBy Bernd Debusmann JrBBC News, WashingtonOne celebrity who missed this year's star-studded event was the fashion designer's cat, Choupette.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 4:164:16Corpse found under Tibet hotel bed leads to probeBy Joel Guinto and Fan Wang in SingaporeA Chinese tourist recalls his holiday gone wrong in an unsavoury review that has since gone viral.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 4:074:07Ugandan minister shot dead by his bodyguardPatience AtuhaireBBC News, KampalaUganda parliamentCopyright: Uganda parliamentRetired Col Charles Okello Engola was shot at his homeImage caption: Retired Col Charles Okello Engola was shot at his homeA Ugandan national army soldier has shot and killed a
government minister whom he was guarding.Retired Col Charles Okello Engola, the deputy
minister for labour, was shot at his home in the capital, Kampala, on Tuesday morning.It is not yet clear whether there was an argument between
the soldier and his boss.Some eyewitness say the soldier walked around the
neighbourhood shooting in the air.The soldier, who is yet to be officially identified, then shot

Raw content part#3: previously served as a deputy minister for defence.Article share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 3:493:49'My wife and six children joined Kenya starvation cult'By Dorcas WangiraBBC News, MalindiKenyans are trying to fathom why more than 100 people may have starved to death in an isolated camp.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 3:393:39Zanzibar profileAn overview of Zanzibar, including key facts about this semi-autonomous island province of Tanzania.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 3:363:36Kenyan cult leader appears in court over mass deathsMark PivacBBC World Service NewsroomGetty ImagesCopyright: Getty ImagesPaul Mackenzie Nthenge is accused of exhorting his followers to starve themselvesImage caption: Paul Mackenzie Nthenge is accused of exhorting his followers to starve themselvesThe leader of a Kenyan doomsday cult has appeared in court, after more than 100 of his followers were found in mass graves last month. Paul Mackenzie Nthenge, a former taxi driver, is accused of exhorting his followers to starve themselves to death to enter heaven before the world ended. Another pastor, the televangelist Ezekiel Odero, is due in a separate court on charges including murder and aiding suicide. On Monday, Kenya’s chief pathologist said the first autopsies of victims - nine children and a woman - indicated death by starvation, and in two cases, asphyxiation.Article share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 3:033:03Kenyan cult leader's wife arrested in coastal townGetty ImagesCopyright: Getty ImagesAutopsies on some 110 bodies of Christian cult members show some victims were killed through suffocationImage caption: Autopsies on some 110 bodies of Christian cult members show some victims were killed through suffocationThe wife of a Kenyan pastor who is scheduled to appear in court on Tuesday over the deaths of congregants has been arrested.Pastor Paul Mackenzie's wife, Rhoda Maweu, was arrested in the coastal town of Mtwapa on Monday night after weeks of being on the run, local media said.She was arrested alongside her aunt Everlyne Nduku Muema. Police say Ms Maweu is a person of interest in the case where the suspected cult has led to the deaths of more than 100 people. She is expected to appear in court on Tuesday alongside her husband. Some of the victims of the cult operating in Kilifi’s Shakahola forest were killed through suffocation and strangulation, post-mortem examinations on some of the 110 bodies exhumed have shown.Mr Mackenzie has denied wrongdoing but has been denied bail. Another pastor Ezekiel Odero who was arrested over similar deaths in his church also based in Kilifi county is also being arraigned in court on Tuesday.Article share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 2:372:37New record as 456,000 Indians take flights in a dayThe milestone was reached on 30 April as 2,978 flights took off across the country.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 2:292:29WFP resumes operations in Sudan despite clashesThe World Food Programme (WFP) has said that it has resumed its operations in Sudan as the fighting in the country threatens millions with hunger.In a statement on Monday, the UN agency said distribution of food is expected to commence in the states of Gedaref, Gezira, Kassala and White Nile in the coming days.“We will take utmost care to ensure the safety of all our staff and partners as we rush to meet the growing needs of the most vulnerable,” the statement said. The WFP suspended operations when three staff members were killed on the first day of the conflict between Sudan’s army and paramilitary Rapid Support Forces (RSF).The agency noted that over 15 million people were already facing severe food insecurity in Sudan before the outbreak of conflict, and these numbers are expected to increase significantly as the fighting continues.Meanwhile, United Nations' emergency relief co-ordinator Martin Griffiths is expected to arrive in Sudan on Tuesday to assess the humanitarian situation in the country.Article share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 2:242:24Indian wrestlers continue protest against 'sex abuse'The athletes have accused their federation chief of sexual harassment - he has denied the allegations.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 2:122:12IPL cricketers fined after fight caught on cameraVirat Kohli and Gautam Gambhir were asked to forfeit match fees after their heated exchange,Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 1:321:32Wheelchair user left to crawl off planeIrishman Adrian Keogh was told help would take an hour to arrive after his flight landed in Sweden.Read morenextArticle share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Page 1 of 50rewindpreviousNavigate to the next pagenextNavigate to the last pageforward

Paul Mackenzie Nthenge, a former taxi driver, is accused of exhorting his followers to starve themselves to death to enter heaven before the world ended. Another pastor, the televangelist Ezekiel Odero, is due in a separate court on charges including murder and aiding suicide. On Monday, Kenya’s chief pathologist said the first autopsies of victims - nine children and a woman - indicated death by starvation, and in two cases, asphyxiation.Article share toolsFacebookTwitterShareView more share optionsShare this postCopy this linkRead more about these links.Posted at 3:033:03Kenyan cult leader's wife arrested in coastal townGetty ImagesCopyright: Getty ImagesAutopsies on some 110 bodies of Christian cult members show some victims were killed through suffocationImage caption: Autopsies on some 110 bodies of Christian cult members show some victims were killed through suffocationThe wife of a Kenyan pastor who is scheduled to appear in court on Tuesday over the deaths of congregants has been arrested.Pastor Paul Mackenzie's wife, Rhoda Maweu, was arrested in the coastal town of Mtwapa on Monday night after weeks of being on the run, local media said.She was arrested alongside her aunt Everlyne Nduku Muema. Police say Ms Maweu is a person of interest in the case where the suspected cult has led to the deaths of more than 100 people. She is expected to appear in court on Tuesday alongside her husband. Some of the victims of the cult operating in Kilifi’s Shakahola forest were killed through suffocation and strangulation, post-mortem examinations on some of the 110 bodies exhumed have shown.Mr Mackenzie has denied wrongdoing but has been denied bail.
